The paper deals with the problem of constructing a minimum-weight spanning tree in a distributed setting, where each edge has a latency and a capacity. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. Additionally, the presence of edge latencies and capacities indicates that the paper could also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category. The paper also involves analyzing the time complexity of the algorithms used to construct the MST, which suggests that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. Furthermore, the paper provides tight bounds on the time complexity, which suggests that it could belong to the Algorithms (cs.AL) category. Finally, the paper involves information theory, as it considers the relationship between edge latencies and weights, which suggests that it could also belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) category.
